1
00:00:00,959 --> 00:00:29,429
Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma sambodasa Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma sambodasa Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma sambodasa Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-awakened one.

2
00:00:31,199 --> 00:00:35,232
So I thought this evening we'd tackle this factor of enlightenment.

3
00:00:35,634 --> 00:00:43,098
The word is Pasadi and it translates as calmness, tranquility, serenity.

4
00:00:44,682 --> 00:00:52,115
And you can see that this is really important because the Buddha's included it in one of the seven factors of enlightenment.

5
00:00:52,777 --> 00:01:00,451
So just to remind you, the seven factors are awareness, and you've got effort and concentration.

6
00:01:01,093 --> 00:01:06,623
You've got this calmness and curiosity, and then you have

7
00:01:07,159 --> 00:01:10,884
equanimity and the investigation of the Dharma.

8
00:01:11,125 --> 00:01:16,209
So the first six are just general virtues that everybody can develop.

9
00:01:16,671 --> 00:01:34,951
What turns them into factors of enlightenment is the investigation of the characteristics of existence, impermanence, how we create suffering for ourselves through wrong attachments, wrong desires, wanting, not wanting, and of course, identity, not self.

10
00:01:35,673 --> 00:01:36,052
Okay.

11
00:01:37,670 --> 00:01:45,221
So I think people who've done, if you've done Yoga Nidra, then I think that's a really deep way of relaxing.

12
00:01:46,802 --> 00:01:52,731
And we have to, yeah, in war zones, you have to keep calm and carry on.

13
00:01:53,533 --> 00:01:57,558
So I don't know whether I want to post that up in present war zones.

14
00:01:58,480 --> 00:01:59,460
Terrible what's happening.

15
00:02:00,963 --> 00:02:01,905
So...

16
00:02:03,403 --> 00:02:06,728
The first, the Buddha always splits everything into body and mind.

17
00:02:07,209 --> 00:02:09,252
So if we look at what happens in the body.

18
00:02:09,793 --> 00:02:10,974
So I did a bit of research.

19
00:02:11,055 --> 00:02:14,379
Most of you know this better than I do, actually, for sure.

20
00:02:15,401 --> 00:02:18,385
Remember, we have autonomic systems.

21
00:02:18,506 --> 00:02:21,651
So one is the sympathetic, one is the parasympathetic.

22
00:02:22,171 --> 00:02:24,936
So the sympathetic one is the fight and flight.

23
00:02:25,736 --> 00:02:28,640
So you're walking across the road and a car suddenly makes for you.

24
00:02:28,921 --> 00:02:30,824
Before you know it, you've got to the other side.

25
00:02:31,125 --> 00:02:33,207
So that's the sympathetic.

26
00:02:33,778 --> 00:03:02,604
nervous system the padawan is the opposite right so it's about calmness rest and digest I've picked that up somewhere it affects your heart rate etc etc we'll come to that in a minute so the big thing about being calm about relaxing into the present moment is physically it releases all these wonderful neurotransmitters serotonin which makes you feel happy and well-being

27
00:03:03,056 --> 00:03:15,800
and feel good factors the endorphins now i remember that in buddhist understanding these uh hormones within the body affect the mind right

28
00:03:16,421 --> 00:03:18,985
So there are two different systems within us.

29
00:03:19,125 --> 00:03:26,973
There's this more gross energy that we call subatomic particles or subatomic energy.

30
00:03:27,794 --> 00:03:31,098
And there's a mental energy which is separate from that.

31
00:03:31,618 --> 00:03:34,300
This you can actually experience in your meditation.

32
00:03:35,162 --> 00:03:40,187
So it's not as though these hormones directly make you happy.

33
00:03:40,247 --> 00:03:44,893
They just have the effect on the heart of making it happy, your emotional life.

34
00:03:45,497 --> 00:03:46,901
And of course, it works the other way.

35
00:03:47,062 --> 00:03:48,806
When you're angry, the body gets hot.

36
00:03:51,834 --> 00:03:53,959
Similarly, it reduces cortisol.

37
00:03:54,019 --> 00:04:01,818
So that's what we have when we've got all this stress related stuff, you know, which isn't very good for us.

38
00:04:02,947 --> 00:04:28,802
because you're relaxed because the body is feeling okay obviously uh it's much better for you for our immune system so we're able to fight um you know diseases um as you know there's a there's a syndrome where people who are stressed at work they go on holiday and then fall ill so it's as though it's as though they have to they have to have a real rest

39
00:04:31,279 --> 00:04:33,584
So it lowers muscle tension.

40
00:04:33,685 --> 00:04:35,487
I mean, that's the whole point of relaxing, isn't it?

41
00:04:35,567 --> 00:04:39,355
To relax the muscles as such.

42
00:04:40,057 --> 00:04:43,142
And this, of course, can alleviate even chronic pain.

43
00:04:44,685 --> 00:04:50,637
Just going back to my first episode with my back, the first time the...

44
00:04:51,512 --> 00:05:01,103
the disc prolapsed, I went along to an acupuncturist and I was surprised that as the needles went in, this anxiety came up.

45
00:05:02,144 --> 00:05:12,012
And as the anxiety dissipated, the pain wasn't anywhere near as bad as when I had this anxiety holding the body as it were for me.

46
00:05:12,394 --> 00:05:13,454
It was trying to protect me.

47
00:05:13,735 --> 00:05:16,557
I mean, these systems are trying to protect us.

48
00:05:18,326 --> 00:05:21,831
And similarly, of course, it helps digestion.

49
00:05:24,014 --> 00:05:30,723
It actually says that stress can lead to digestive issues such as indigestion, irritable bowel syndrome.

50
00:05:30,744 --> 00:05:35,310
So especially to feel relaxed around eating.

51
00:05:36,071 --> 00:05:43,180
I mean, if you're at work and you're being pressured and you're just chucking the sandwich down your throat, can't be doing you good, can it?

52
00:05:44,041 --> 00:05:47,507
And in Eastern understanding, I was thinking of the Chinese.

53
00:05:48,077 --> 00:05:53,423
11 o'clock to 1 o'clock is eating time.

54
00:05:53,562 --> 00:05:56,966
So your body is primed to eat at that time.

55
00:05:57,786 --> 00:06:01,990
And from 1 o'clock to 3 o'clock is liver time, right?

56
00:06:02,350 --> 00:06:09,557
So if you're rushing around while your liver's trying to handle all these nutrients, you can see it's not going to do you very good.

57
00:06:10,317 --> 00:06:15,041
So between 11 and 3 o'clock, make an effort to be a bit more relaxed.

58
00:06:15,062 --> 00:06:16,362
That's if you're stressed, yeah?

59
00:06:18,418 --> 00:06:22,783
As a change in brain activity, you get these lovely alpha brain waves.

60
00:06:23,225 --> 00:06:26,689
So these are the ones that you have when you're feeling relaxed.

61
00:06:26,728 --> 00:06:28,690
It's also a very creative place to be.

62
00:06:29,591 --> 00:06:31,475
And we're there when we meditate.

63
00:06:32,115 --> 00:06:39,524
So when you're actually in that state of just vipassana, normally the mind will go down to these alpha waves.

64
00:06:42,327 --> 00:06:44,410
And obviously it improves your sleep because

65
00:06:44,862 --> 00:06:49,869
You know, if you're not calm when you're trying to sleep, it's difficult, yeah?

66
00:06:49,889 --> 00:07:02,247
I mean, that's why really, you know, to close everything down about half an hour before we intend to sleep, you know, get off the social media, turn off Netflix, the BBC.

67
00:07:03,120 --> 00:07:05,483
and do something which is going to calm us.

68
00:07:05,925 --> 00:07:16,939
I personally sometimes listen to the chanting from Throstle Hole Abbey, which was my first Buddhist encounter, and I just love their chanting.

69
00:07:17,238 --> 00:07:27,593
But there's other types of music, read poetry, there's many things you can do that are just relaxing in order to be prepared to go into sleep, you see.

70
00:07:28,382 --> 00:07:33,309
What we want to do is get that substrate under sleep to be calm and peaceful.

71
00:07:33,970 --> 00:07:41,619
And of course, when we're in bed, to put the breath, to put the attention on the breath and just feel it, just feel the body breathing.

72
00:07:41,899 --> 00:07:43,942
See, it wafts you into sleep, very calm.

73
00:07:44,942 --> 00:07:47,326
I can do metta, of course, yeah.

74
00:07:47,346 --> 00:07:52,112
But the big thing is this sense of being relaxed, of being at ease.

75
00:07:54,843 --> 00:07:56,384
I'm actually reading a book on this.

76
00:07:56,605 --> 00:08:01,812
It was a Sunday Times bestseller called Breath by James Nestor.

77
00:08:02,254 --> 00:08:03,375
It's entertaining.

78
00:08:04,156 --> 00:08:04,737
It's very good.

79
00:08:08,101 --> 00:08:16,634
When we relax, when we feel calm, even in situations that are stressful, we can get into a calmer place.

80
00:08:16,654 --> 00:08:20,901
It's obviously having these effects on the body and that's got to be good for us.

81
00:08:23,480 --> 00:08:38,495
When it comes to citta-pāsati, the calmness, tranquility of the heart, obviously the stress is happening the other way.

82
00:08:38,777 --> 00:08:46,585
It's coming as a reaction we have to a given situation or person.

83
00:08:47,509 --> 00:08:51,498
that stress coming in the heart is moving back into the body.

84
00:08:51,979 --> 00:09:01,317
So as soon as we can, you know, just relax around something which is upsetting us, making us anxious, all the better.

85
00:09:04,047 --> 00:09:19,296
And of course, if we have a sort of habit of being calm in situation, it should extend itself into situations which are stressful, which means that we're slightly more emotionally resilient.

86
00:09:19,355 --> 00:09:21,038
We can move our emotions a bit.

87
00:09:21,099 --> 00:09:27,591
We're not stuck on one groove of being angry or being anxious or getting depressed about something.

88
00:09:30,085 --> 00:09:34,389
And of course, when you are calm, it just improves your decision making.

89
00:09:35,350 --> 00:09:40,596
I make a rule for myself, which whenever I break it, it's always disastrous.

90
00:09:41,216 --> 00:09:49,024
I try never to make any decision when I'm miffed or angry, when I'm anxious or when I'm in doubt.

91
00:09:49,585 --> 00:09:55,029
If I make a decision in those states of mind, something bad turns up.

92
00:09:56,477 --> 00:09:58,423
So you have to wait sometimes.

93
00:09:58,442 --> 00:10:02,494
You have to wait until there's calmness and then there's greater clarity.

94
00:10:04,659 --> 00:10:07,287
It's obviously better for our relationships too, isn't it?

95
00:10:07,346 --> 00:10:11,618
I mean, you know, if you're with somebody who's neurotic, it sort of affects you, doesn't it?

96
00:10:11,884 --> 00:10:14,067
And if you're a neurotic, it affects them.

97
00:10:14,727 --> 00:10:32,547
So if we can, if we can sort of get into the habit of just being calm, not rushing, you know, in conversation, you know, not trying to get the answer ready before the person stopped talking, you know, but to actually get into that mode of listening and to listen, you've got to be calm, right?

98
00:10:32,567 --> 00:10:34,129
You've got to be open.

99
00:10:36,792 --> 00:10:39,215
It's obviously a good place for creativity.

100
00:10:39,695 --> 00:10:41,537
We're not talking about, you know,

101
00:10:42,326 --> 00:10:48,841
you know, winners of the Booker Prize or ecstatic artists.

102
00:10:49,883 --> 00:10:52,928
It's just daily being creative about what we do.

103
00:10:53,571 --> 00:10:58,360
So even washing the pots can be actually a creative action, right?

104
00:10:58,701 --> 00:11:00,504
You can find different ways of doing it.

105
00:11:01,986 --> 00:11:07,013
This creativity, I mean, every moment, every day is different.

106
00:11:07,092 --> 00:11:10,817
So without us knowing it, we've got to be creative, right?

107
00:11:10,837 --> 00:11:14,461
Even if you're driving a car, you've got to be creative.

108
00:11:14,481 --> 00:11:15,864
You've got to see where you're going.

109
00:11:15,884 --> 00:11:21,510
You've got to drive in a safe and easy way and feel relaxed.

110
00:11:22,030 --> 00:11:29,039
So you know what happens when you drive and you're tense and you're anxious to get to a place or you're late to get to a place.

111
00:11:29,121 --> 00:11:34,009
So that's how accidents happen.

112
00:11:36,494 --> 00:11:41,462
So obviously being calm just has an effect on our mental health.

113
00:11:42,585 --> 00:11:50,017
And, you know, developing that as a base within our lives from which we move, right?

114
00:11:50,037 --> 00:11:52,881
Out of that base, you sort of move into an action.

115
00:11:52,902 --> 00:11:55,145
I mean, it's going to make us happy, hasn't it?

116
00:11:56,543 --> 00:11:58,607
Remember, these things are just habits.

117
00:11:58,729 --> 00:12:00,373
They're just habits that we can develop.

118
00:12:02,298 --> 00:12:07,410
So, OK, so it obviously has an effect on the body and it affects on the heart.

119
00:12:08,273 --> 00:12:13,826
And so it now becomes a Bojanga, which is a factor of enlightenment.

120
00:12:14,616 --> 00:12:18,241
And it looms quite large in the Buddha's teachings.

121
00:12:18,322 --> 00:12:22,408
It's normally connected to concentration, calm concentration.

122
00:12:22,508 --> 00:12:27,695
Samatha is the word for calming exercises.

123
00:12:27,754 --> 00:12:31,019
So metta practice would be a samatha practice.

124
00:12:32,280 --> 00:12:35,826
And it leads into an easy concentration.

125
00:12:37,688 --> 00:12:42,294
If you want to be concentrated, the worst thing you can do is to try to be concentrated.

126
00:12:42,663 --> 00:12:54,719
The whole thing about concentration comes when you're relaxed and at ease and just placing the attention on the object and allowing the concentration to manifest.

127
00:12:54,739 --> 00:13:01,447
As soon as you try and push the process, you're getting in the way and what you get is restlessness.

128
00:13:02,812 --> 00:13:04,575
So you find it in the Eightfold Path.

129
00:13:04,634 --> 00:13:07,698
The last three are to do with mindfulness.

130
00:13:07,818 --> 00:13:12,044
It's right effort, right mindfulness, right concentration.

131
00:13:12,605 --> 00:13:16,091
And we can include in that concentration that sense of calmness.

132
00:13:18,134 --> 00:13:20,336
It's one of the four divine abidings.

133
00:13:20,498 --> 00:13:22,259
So we've got love, compassion.

134
00:13:22,320 --> 00:13:26,326
They're called divine abidings, also illimitables.

135
00:13:26,726 --> 00:13:31,013
But there are social virtues, the love, compassion, joy, and

136
00:13:31,177 --> 00:13:33,259
There the word is upeka.

137
00:13:33,279 --> 00:13:40,187
And this is where you get that sort of touching of calmness and equanimity.

138
00:13:40,788 --> 00:13:43,730
So equanimity has to rest upon calmness.

139
00:13:44,331 --> 00:13:47,815
You can't be equanimous if you're all agitated.

140
00:13:48,596 --> 00:13:54,842
Equanimous, in my understanding, refers to a certain attitude, a certain way of looking at things.

141
00:13:55,342 --> 00:13:58,907
Calmness is your mental state and it's supporting it.

142
00:14:01,840 --> 00:14:03,623
Yes, it's in meditation.

143
00:14:03,722 --> 00:14:15,219
The concentration of the Samatha practice, of course, leads to an even deeper sense of relaxation through the practice of jhana, through the practice of absorptions.

144
00:14:15,659 --> 00:14:18,082
So it's right there within the practice.

145
00:14:18,163 --> 00:14:19,725
It's not something that we add on.

146
00:14:20,246 --> 00:14:22,649
It's a necessary part of our practice.

147
00:14:23,947 --> 00:14:47,706
And when we are calm and we're not restless, whenever something arises, which is obstructing our meditation, messing us about in ordinary daily life, even from minor silly things to sort of heavy mental states, that calmness, if we've got that substrate of calmness, we can deal with it.

148
00:14:48,467 --> 00:14:49,009
That's the point.

149
00:14:52,785 --> 00:14:56,130
And then finally, of course, there is the great calmness itself.

150
00:14:57,734 --> 00:15:07,408
In the Metta Sutta, remember, it talks about what must be done for those people who wish to reach the state of peace.

151
00:15:08,049 --> 00:15:10,614
Now, they use a different word there, Santa.

152
00:15:10,894 --> 00:15:15,822
But of course, it is this calmness, this state of sublime serenity.

153
00:15:16,363 --> 00:15:19,687
That's one of the adjectives the Buddha uses for Nibbāna.

154
00:15:21,793 --> 00:15:22,654
So there we are.

155
00:15:23,035 --> 00:15:30,586
So I'm hoping that you're all convinced and that to develop our calmness is absolutely necessary.

156
00:15:31,368 --> 00:15:39,038
And just remind yourself, it could become part of your New Year resolutions.

157
00:15:39,058 --> 00:15:40,341
It's a bit late, but why not?

158
00:15:40,441 --> 00:15:43,144
We can always add them on, can't we?

159
00:15:43,424 --> 00:15:46,249
And to sort of...

160
00:15:47,004 --> 00:16:00,923
get in the habit, something I've been working on all my life since I became a Buddhist, is to, when you finish something, when you've done a task, it can be just like, you know, the washing of the pots, but it could be a piece of work.

161
00:16:01,004 --> 00:16:03,726
It could be a bit of gardening you've done, not this time of course.

162
00:16:04,508 --> 00:16:13,059
And when it's finished, just to sort of relax for a moment and just reflect on what you've done and see how you feel about it.

163
00:16:15,102 --> 00:16:15,442
Yeah.

164
00:16:15,980 --> 00:16:21,288
And then just to stop for a moment, just to relax into the present moment, you see.

165
00:16:21,308 --> 00:16:24,674
And then quite naturally, the next thing to be done will arise, you see.

166
00:16:25,135 --> 00:16:29,984
So you're moving into the next thing to be done from that base of calmness.

167
00:16:31,687 --> 00:16:36,434
And that allows us to be more wise, more loving, you know.

168
00:16:37,816 --> 00:16:51,740
So I'm hoping that I've convinced you to really practice this quality of calmness and that by your devotion to it, you will be liberated from all suffering sooner rather than later.

